<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06044066 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06044066 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FOOD; RECIPE; LIST  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  FRENCH fries are best when deep fried and homemade chocolate cake deserves itstime in a conventional oven, but here are 10 foods best left for the microwaveoven:;    (check) Fish: Fresh or thawed fish fillets, covered and steam-cookedin the microwave oven, come out perfect -- moist and tender. No dried out topfrom broiling, no fat from frying.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Food  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TRUST US; THESE 10 FOODS COOK BETTER IN MICROWAVE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Tips  </MEMO><TEXT>     (check) Cauliflower: Microwaves hit a whole head on all sides so it cooksevenly. A whole head, covered with plastic wrap, takes six to eight minutes onhigh power. No water to boil. Less nutrient loss.;    (check) Sweet potatoes:No concerns over crisp skin because most people don't eat sweet potato skin.And the moist, heavy interior benefits from the steaming effect of themicrowave. One potato cooked on high power takes about five minutes, fourmedium-sized potatoes, 12 to 14 minutes.;    (check) Whole beets: No more potsof red-dyed water. And the beet's round shape is ideal for even cooking in themicrowave oven. One pound of two-inch diameter beets need only 14 to 18minutes on high power.;    (check) Corn-on-the-cob: Corn cooked in themicrowave oven has a moist, steamed texture. You don't have to husk the cornbefore it's cooked; in fact, the husks add an earthy flavor to the kernels.After cooking (four ears need 10 to 12 minutes on high power), the silkytassels slip off easily.;    (check) Rice: Cooking rice in the microwave ovenis a one-step process if you have an oven that allows you to program twocooking powers and times. (Stir one cup of rice into two cups of roomtemperature water; cover, set on high power for five minutes, then 50 percentpower for 12.);    (check) Oatmeal-in-a-bowl: A single serving of one-minuteoats is ready in about 1 1/2 minutes.;    (check) Chocolate: No double boilerto clean. No threat of burning the chocolate. Unsweetened baking chocolatemelts right in a glass measuring cup (use medium power, not high), ready forbaking or dessert sauces.;    (check) Mixed vegetable plate: An assortment offresh vegetables can be piled on a plate and cooked at the same time. For bestresults, cut vegetables in similar shapes and put slow-cooking vegetables onthe outside of the dish, fast-cooking ones on the inside.;    (check) Stuffedgreen peppers: No need to pre-boil the peppers. And the peppers keep a livelygreen color and just-crisp texture.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  PATRICIA TENNISON, Chicago Tribune  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910213  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  9D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  415  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday February 13, 199100044066,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>